Almouse 09-May-17 06:56 PM
anyone for some panorama thing that's probably really dumb but i don't understand?
i am writing code to dynamically generate buttons
for example, i have a table with elements a,b,c,d,e, and the code generates one button for each table element, with the intent that clicking the button calls a function based on the table element
for(var i = 0; i < results.length; i++) { var button = $.CreatePanel( "Button", subcategoryPanel, "" ); button.SetPanelEvent("onactivate", function(){$.Msg(i); panel.UpdateResults(results[i])} ) //
the problem is that the 'i' in the setpanelevent is the variable i, not the current value of i (at the time the setpanelevent was allocated)
so every button ends up calling the same function
Broccoli 09-May-17 06:59 PM
it's a javascript async call issue
basically create another function to do button.SetPanelEvent("onactivate", function(){$.Msg(i); panel.UpdateResults(results[i])} )
K1dney 09-May-17 07:00 PM
button.i = i
lol
i am dumb
Broccoli 09-May-17 07:01 PM
basically when you press the button, the i will always return as results.length because of referencing (edited)
you can solve it by dereferencing it
so you'll need
function dummy(button, i){ button.SetPanelEvent("onactivate", function(){$.Msg(i); panel.UpdateResults(results[i])} ) }
and in your for loop, call that dummy function

<Perry> difference between events and nettables is that you can selectively send events to players, but everyone has all the nettables
<Perry> also events require some logic to make sure you land in the proper state if you DC/reconnect
<Perry> because it just drops all events while you're not connected
